<section xml:id="section-fractions">

    <title>Fractions and Fraction Arithmetic</title>

    <subsection>
        
        <title>Loving Fractions</title>
        
        <p>Many people hate fractions. This is understandable, since fraction arithmeitc seems to be presented as torture to many elementary school students. But hating fractions is terrible. Fractions are for sharing, and sharing is good. So it's important that we all work on learning to love fractions. Love is difficult without understanding, so let's work on understanding fractions better.</p>

        <p>The word <q>fraction</q> comes from the Latin word <em>fractio</em>, which means <q>break into pieces.</q> If we use a rectangle to represent a whole amount, we can sketch fractions to help us develop our understanding of these numbers. (At least one of the authors still sketches fractions like this to help themself understand fractions better.)</p>

        <todo>illustrations of 1 whole amount and 3/7 of that whole amount</todo>

        <p>In the figure, we see <m>1</m> whole amount divided into <m>7</m> parts. Since <m>3</m> of the <m>7</m> parts are highlighted, we have an illustration of the fraction <m>\frac{3}{7}</m>. The denominator <m>7</m> lets us know how many equal parts of the whole amount we're considering; since we've got <m>7</m> parts here, they're called <q>sevenths</q>. The <term>numerator</term> <m>3</m> tells us how many of those sevenths we're considering.</p>


        <todo>Same figure as above into exercise statement.</todo>
        <todo>figure with highligthed whole amount after first p in solution</todo>
        <todo>figure with seven thirds highlighted after second p in solution</todo>

        <exercise>
            <statement> 
                <p>Identify the whole amount and the parts we're considerig in the figure for the fraction <m>\frac{7}{3}</m>.</p>
            </statement>

            <solution>
                <p>Looking for seven thirds, we must identify <m>3</m> equal parts as our whole.</p>
                <p>Then we can identify <m>7</m> of those parts as our fractional amount.</p>
                <p>We can use the same illustration for fractions <m>\frac{3}{7}</m> and <m>\frac{7}{3}</m> (fractions for which the roles of numerator and denominator are reversed are called <term>reciprocals</term>), but we need to change our perspective to <em>see</em> the whole amount of interest.</p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <p>We can also represent fractions on number lines. When a number line is marked off with whole numbers, we use the unit <m>1</m> as our whole amount, and equal divisions of the unit <m>1</m> for our equal parts like so:</p>

        <todo>(reciprocals 3/7 and 7/3 on two number lines.)</todo>

        <p>As soon as we'd like to graph fractions with different denominators on the same number line, the picture gets more complicated. To graph both <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> and <m>\frac{2}{5}</m> on the same number line, we need to divide up our whole so we can see <m>3</m> equal parts and <m>5</m> equal parts. That requires us to divide the unit <m>1</m> into <m>3 \cdot 5 = 15</m> equal parts like so:</p>

        <todo>(number line with both 2/3 and 2/5 graphed carefully.)</todo>

        <p>How about rectangular sketches for <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> and <m>\frac{2}{5}</m> on the same scale? We can break <m>1</m> whole amount into parts more than one way:</p>

        <todo>(Look at “candy bars” representing 1, 2/3, and 2/5.)</todo>

        <p>On both the number line and the rectangular sketches, we can see <m>15</m> equal parts. Then <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> is the same part of the whole as <m>\frac{10}{15}</m>. That means <m>\frac{2}{3} = \frac{10}{15}</m>. We can also see that <m>\frac{2}{5}=\frac{6}{15}</m>. <term>Equivalent fractions</term> are fractions written with different numerators and denominators which both represent the same part of a whole.</p>

        <p>Loving fractions is challenging, but if we focus on the the basic idea that <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> means <q>two of three equal parts of a whole amount</q> and we have a few ways to <em>see</em> that value, we've got the basic understanding we need.</p>

        <p>Once we've got some love for fractions, we start to notice them everywhere. Especially in recipes.</p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Mixed Numbers and Improper Fractions</title>
        <p>A simple recipe for bread contains only a few ingredients:</p>

        <todo>reference</todo>
        <table xml:id="table-bread-recipe">
            <caption>Ingredients for simple crusty bread.</caption>
            <tabular>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>1\, 1/2</m></cell>
                    <cell>tablespoons yeast</cell>
                </row>         
                <row>
                    <cell><m>1\, 1/2</m></cell>
                    <cell>tablespoons kosher salt</cell>
                </row>         
                <row>
                    <cell><m>6\, 1/2</m></cell>
                    <cell>cups unbleached, all-purpose flour (more for dusting)</cell>
                </row>  
            </tabular>       
        </table>

        <p>Each ingredient is listed as a <term>mixed number</term> that quickly communicates how many whole amounts and how many parts are needed. Unfortunately, mixed number notation didn't catch on among mathematicians or computer scientists, so we will need to use <term>improper fractions</term> (fractions whose numerators are greater than their denominators) to represent these amounts in our work. How to do so?</p>

        <todo>Should this be an Example?</todo>
        <p>Let's <q>see</q> the fraction for <m>1\, 1/2</m> tablespoons of yeast using the number line:</p>

        <todo>(Picture of 1 1/2 on the number line)</todo>

        <p>On the number line, we quickly <q>see</q> that there are <m>3</m> halves, so <m>1\, 1/2 = 3/2</m>.</p>

        <p>Let’s look at <m>6\, 1/2</m> cups of flour using our sketches of whole amounts.</p>

        <todo>(Picture of 6 1/2 whole rectangles)</todo>

        <p>With <m>6</m> whole cups, we have <m>6 \cdot 2 = 12</m> half cups, or the fraction <m>\frac{12}{2}</m>. Adding one more half cup, we have <m>6\, 1/2 + 1/2 = 12/2 + 1/2 = 13/2</m> cups of flour.</p>


        <p>Here's a reminder of how adding fractions with the same denominator works. Since <m>\frac{12}{2}</m> means <q>twelve halves</q> and <m>\frac{1}{2}</m> means <q>one half,</q> <m>\frac{12}{2} + \frac{1}{2}</m> must mean <q>twelve halves plus one more half</q> or <q>thirteen halves.</q> Using mathematical symbols, we write <m>\frac{12}{2} + \frac{1}{2} = \frac{12+1}{2} = \frac{13}{2}</m>. Adding <m>12</m> and <m>1</m> in the numerator makes sense because the terms <m>12</m> and <m>1</m> both represent amounts of halves. That gives a rule for adding fractions with the same denominator: <m>\frac{a}{b} + \frac{c}{b} = \frac{a+c}{b}</m>.</p> 
    </subsection>

