    <subsection>
        <title>Multiplying and dividing fractions</title>
        <p>To double or half a recipe, we need to consider fractions of fractions. Say a recipe calls for ⅔ cup of milk, but we’d like to double it. Using rectangular sketches exactly how we’d use a measuring cup in life we have:</p>

        <todo>(two rectangles with ⅔ highlighted)</todo>

        <p>So <m>\frac{2}{3} \cdot 2 = \frac{4}{3}</m>. This sketch shows <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> of two wholes. Two wholes can be written as <m>2</m>, or as the fraction <m>\frac{2}{1}</m>. So mathematically, our figure says <m>\frac{2}{3} \cdot 2 = \frac{2}{3} \cdot \frac{2}{1} = \frac{4}{3}</m>.</p>

        <p>We can also see this on the number line:</p>

        <todo>(number line indicated two 2/3s)</todo>

        <p>The number line also shows that <m>\frac{2}{3} \cdot 2 = \frac{4}{3}</m>.</p>

        <p>We can also use multiplication to decrease amounts. How much is <m>\frac{1}{2}</m> of <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> cup? Looking at a sketch of <m>\frac{2}{3}</m>:</p>

        <todo>(rectangular sketch showing ⅔)</todo>

        <p>We can <q>break</q> that in half like so:</p>

        <todo>(rectangular sketch showing 1/2 of ⅔)</todo>

        <p>So <m>\frac{1}{2}</m> of <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> cup is <m>\frac{2}{6}</m> cup. Mathematically, we can write <m>\frac{2}{3} \cdot \frac{1}{2} = \frac{2}{6}</m>.</p>

        <p>This idea works generally, no matter what amounts we use: <m>\frac{a}{b} \cdot \frac{c}{d} = \frac{a\cdot c}{b \cdot d}</m>.</p>

        <p>Multiplication works when we ask about <q>How much is this fraction of that amount?</q> Division answers the question <q>How many of those amounts fit into that amount?</q></p>

        <p>Suppose a baker lost their <m>\frac{1}{3}</m> cup measuring cup, and wanted to use a <m>\frac{1}{2}</m> cup measuring cup to measure out <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> cup of brown sugar. They'd need to answer <q>How many <m>\frac{1}{2}</m> cups are in <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> cup?</q> That is, they'd need to find <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> divided by <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>. Let's start by sketching amounts:</p>

<todo>(sketch of ⅔, sketch of 1/2)</todo>

        <p>Remember that love for fractions depends on understanding which whole amount has our attention. When we ask <q>How many <m>\frac{1}{2}</m> cups are in <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> cup?</q> we are asking about a number of <m>\frac{1}{2}</m> cups. That means that the <em>whole</em> amount in this division problem is a <m>\frac{1}{2}</m> cup. Okay, let's look back at the situation with both thirds and halves in the same picture:</p>
        
        <todo>(sketch of ⅔ with 1/2 as well)</todo>

        <p>Can you see how many halves are in <m>\frac{2}{3}</m>?</p>

        <todo>(sketch of ⅔ with 1/2 labeled as “whole”)</todo>

        <p>There <m>\frac{4}{3}</m> halves in <m>\frac{2}{3}</m>. That means that <m>\frac{2}{3} \div \frac{1}{2} = \frac{4}{3}</m>.</p>

        <p>If we look back at the sketch, and ask <q>How much is <m>\frac{2}{1}</m> of <m>\frac{2}{3}</m>?</q> Looking carefully, we <q>see</q> that <m>\frac{2}{3} \cdot \frac{2}{1} = \frac{4}{3}</m>. We've sketched both division and multiplication in one sketch. If we love fractions enough, we can <q>see</q> that <m>\frac{2}{3} \div \frac{1}{2} = \frac{2}{3} \cdot \frac{2}{1} = \frac{4}{3}</m>.</p>

        <p>This works no matter what amounts we use as well: <m>\frac{a}{b} \div \frac{c}{d} = \frac{a}{b} \cdot \frac{d}{c} = \frac{ad}{bc}</m></p>
    </subsection>


    <subsection>
        <title>Adding and subtracting fractions</title>
        
        <p>With whole numbers and integers, operations of addition and subtraction are simple. As long as fractions are given with the same denominator, the situation remains simple as we discussed working with mixed numbers above, <me>\frac{12}{2} + \frac{1}{2} = \frac{12+1}{2} = \frac{13}{2}</me>.</p>

        <p>Whenever we'd like to combine fractional amounts that don't represent the same number of parts of a whole, finding sums and differences is more complicated. Luckily, we've already done some of the work. Let's add the fractions <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> and <m>\frac{2}{5}</m> together.</p>

        <p>To graph both <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> and <m>\frac{2}{5}</m> on the same number line, we needed to see the values as equivalent fractions <m>\frac{10}{15}</m> and <m>\frac{6}{15}</m>. Adding those amounts works just like addition on the number line.</p>

        <todo>(number line picture of 10/15 + 6/15 = 16/15)</todo>

        <p>So <m>\frac{10}{15} + \frac{6}{15} = \frac{10+6}{15} = \frac{16}{15}</m>. Finding the sum of the numerators makes sense because we're adding equal-sized parts of the whole (fifteenths) together. Those equal-sized parts of the whole are called the <term>common denominator</term>.</p>

        <p>To see this idea another way, let's look again at our sketches of both values, breaking the whole two ways:</p>

        <todo>(rectangular sketches of ⅔ and ⅖)</todo>

        <p>Now if we divide both sketches further so we can see fifteenths of both wholes, we can see the sum:</p>

        <todo>(rectangular sketches of 10/15 and 6/15)</todo>

        <p>Mathematically, dividing both sketches into fifteenths works like this: <me>\frac{2}{3} + \frac{2}{5} = \frac{2 \cdot 5}{3 \cdot 5} + \frac{2 \cdot 3}{5 \cdot 3} = \frac{10}{15} + \frac{6}{15}</me> Multiplying both the numerator and denominator of a fraction doesn't affect the amount it represents<mdash />doing so always gives an equivalent fraction. To add or subtract fractions, we first must rewrite the fractions as equivalent fractions with a common denominator.</p>

        <p>A baker needed to subtract <m>\frac{1}{8}</m> cup from <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> cup. (She'd read a recipe slightly out of order.) Mathematically, that’s <me>\frac{2}{3} - \frac{1}{8} = \frac{2 \cdot 8}{3 \cdot 8} - \frac{1 \cdot 3}{8 \cdot 3} = \frac{16}{24} - \frac{3}{24} = \frac{13}{24}</me> cup.</p>


        <p>Generally, building a common denominator for addition works like so: <me>\frac{a}{b} + \frac{c}{d} = \frac{ad}{bd} + \frac{bc}{bd} = \frac{ad + bc}{bd}</me> And for subtraction:
